  childSummary:"An electric train is like a GIANT electric toy car that gets its power from a wire above the track! A special arm on the roof (called a pantograph) touches the wire, and electricity flows down into powerful motors that spin the wheels. Steel wheels on steel rails create very little friction — that's why trains can carry thousands of people using much less energy than cars. When the train needs to slow down, the motors work BACKWARDS — becoming generators that turn the train's motion back into electricity, which goes back into the wire for OTHER trains to use! Special signals and computers make sure two trains are never on the same piece of track at the same time, keeping everyone safe.",
